{
  "id": "unit-03-lesson-02",
  "unit_id": "unit-03",
  "name": "The Full Article System",
  "order": 2,
  "grammar_tips": [
    {
      "id": "unit-03-lesson-02-tip-01",
      "title": "The — More Than One Way to Say It",
      "explanation": "English has one word for 'the'. Italian has several, and the right one depends on the noun's gender and what letter it starts with. Don't panic — most of the time you'll use just 'il' (masculine) or 'la' (feminine). The others handle special cases.",
      "table": [
        ["Article", "Used before", "Example"],
        ["il", "most masculine nouns", "il libro"],
        ["lo", "s+consonant, z, gn, ps", "lo studente, lo zaino"],
        ["la", "most feminine nouns", "la penna"],
        ["l'", "any vowel (masc or fem)", "l'uomo, l'acqua"]
      ],
      "before_exercise": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "unit-03-lesson-02-tip-02",
      "title": "Why 'lo' Exists",
      "explanation": "Say 'il studente' out loud — that 'l-st' mash-up is hard to pronounce. Italian hates consonant clusters at word boundaries, so it uses 'lo' instead: 'lo studente'. Same reason for 'lo zaino', 'lo specchio'. It's not random — it's phonology. Your mouth will thank you.",
      "before_exercise": 6
    },
    {
      "id": "unit-03-lesson-02-tip-03",
      "title": "Uno and Un' — The Indefinite Side",
      "explanation": "You already know 'un' (masculine) and 'una' (feminine). Two more: 'uno' goes before the same consonant clusters as 'lo' (uno studente, uno zaino). 'Un'' (with apostrophe) is 'una' shortened before a feminine vowel: un'amica, un'acqua.",
      "before_exercise": 12
    }
  ],
